Piraha is one of the most interesting languages of all time.

811
00:50:49,920 --> 00:50:53,040
It's spoken by an indigenous group of about 700 people

812
00:50:53,040 --> 00:50:54,640
living in the Brazilian jungle.

813
00:50:54,640 --> 00:50:59,120
The first notable fact is that it only has eight consonants and three vowels,

814
00:50:59,120 --> 00:51:03,040
making it one of the most simple sound systems out of any known language.

815
00:51:03,040 --> 00:51:05,120
It also has some of the rarest sounds,

816
00:51:05,120 --> 00:51:07,200
one of which sounds like blowing a raspberry.

817
00:51:07,200 --> 00:51:09,520
But the limited set of sounds isn't a problem,

818
00:51:09,520 --> 00:51:12,000
since it incorporates a lot of different tones

819
00:51:12,000 --> 00:51:15,840
that allow it to be sung, hummed, or whistled in conversation.

820
00:51:15,840 --> 00:51:17,120
And here's the big one.

821
00:51:17,120 --> 00:51:20,160
Piraha doesn't have any words for numbers.

822
00:51:20,160 --> 00:51:22,640
It does have words for vague quantities,

823
00:51:22,640 --> 00:51:27,600
like a small size or amount, or a bit of a larger size or amount, and a bunch.

824
00:51:27,600 --> 00:51:28,880
So how do they count?

825
00:51:28,880 --> 00:51:31,920
Well, some anthropological evidence seems to suggest

826
00:51:31,920 --> 00:51:33,680
that they simply don't.

827
00:51:33,680 --> 00:51:36,320
At one point, their counting skills were put to a test.

828
00:51:36,320 --> 00:51:39,600
Objects like batteries were placed on a table in a line,

829
00:51:39,600 --> 00:51:43,360
and the Piraha were asked to make a second line just like the first.

830
00:51:43,360 --> 00:51:44,960
This was no problem for them.

831
00:51:44,960 --> 00:51:48,640
Then, a line of objects was created again, hidden from view,

832
00:51:48,640 --> 00:51:50,720
and they were asked to do the same thing.

833
00:51:50,720 --> 00:51:54,640
They were able to do it accurately if there were only two or three objects in the set,

834
00:51:54,640 --> 00:51:57,760
but anything above that resulted in a lot of mistakes.

835
00:51:57,760 --> 00:52:01,760
This indicates that they aren't precisely counting at all during this task,

836
00:52:01,840 --> 00:52:04,480
and instead they're just kind of visually estimating it.

837
00:52:04,480 --> 00:52:08,080
So presumably, counting was never super important for the Piraha,

838
00:52:08,080 --> 00:52:09,600
so they never ended up developing it.

839
00:52:10,560 --> 00:52:17,760
Research from MIT indicates the Pidaha may be the only culture on earth without any numeracy.

840
00:52:17,760 --> 00:52:20,400
The Pidaha don't have numbers because they don't need them.

841
00:52:20,400 --> 00:52:22,080
They survive just fine without them.

842
00:52:23,120 --> 00:52:25,760
In a way, this seems like a pretty comfy way to live.

843
00:52:25,760 --> 00:52:28,800
They aren't concerned about their bank balance, their follower count,

844
00:52:28,800 --> 00:52:31,280
their heart rate, or how many calories they've eaten.

845
00:52:31,280 --> 00:52:34,400
If they were watching a sports game, they wouldn't care about the score.

846
00:52:34,400 --> 00:52:36,080
They'd just sit back and enjoy the game.

