00:55:09,520 --> 00:55:12,640
Once again, we're brought back to the Sapir-Warf hypothesis.

884
00:55:12,640 --> 00:55:16,320
In the 1940s, Warf was working on his linguistic theories,

885
00:55:16,320 --> 00:55:20,560
and studying a language from the Hopi people, a Native American group in Arizona.

886
00:55:20,560 --> 00:55:23,760
It seemed to him that their language was missing a key feature.

887
00:55:23,760 --> 00:55:27,840
They didn't seem to have any words or grammar related to time.

888
00:55:27,840 --> 00:55:34,080
He concluded that they have no general notion or intuition of time as a smooth flowing continuum,

889
00:55:34,080 --> 00:55:36,960
in which everything in the universe proceeds at equal rate,

890
00:55:36,960 --> 00:55:40,480
out of a future, through the present, into a past.

891
00:55:40,480 --> 00:55:44,400
If this was true, this would be fantastic news for his hypothesis,

892
00:55:44,400 --> 00:55:48,320
since it shows a direct connection between their language and their view of the world.

893
00:55:48,320 --> 00:55:52,800
It was a bit too good to be true, though, and it was later proven wrong by Eckhart Malotki,

894
00:55:52,800 --> 00:55:57,200
who ended up finding tons of examples of words and grammar in the Hopi language

895
00:55:57,200 --> 00:55:59,280
that involved relations across time.

896
00:55:59,280 --> 00:56:03,840
The issue was that while the tense system in English emphasizes past and non-past,

897
00:56:03,840 --> 00:56:07,600
the Hopi language is oriented towards future and non-future.

898
00:56:07,600 --> 00:56:13,600
The myth still lives on, though, with smug new-agers saying that Westerners are too obsessed with time,

899
00:56:13,600 --> 00:56:15,840
always carrying a watch to keep track of it.

900
00:56:15,840 --> 00:56:19,040
